The Royal Bank of Scotland Group plc Key Developments

RBS Likely To Avoid Sale Of Williams & Glyn Branches 
Jul 26 17
The Royal Bank of Scotland Group plc (LSE:RBS) is likely to avoid the compulsory sale of its Williams & Glyn branches by doling out £835 million to help boost competition among UK banks. It follows a joint review by the European Commission (EC) and HM Treasury, which have put forward the ``alternative remedies package'' that will help fulfill RBS's state aid obligations following its Government bailout at the height of the financial crisis. The proposal, which still requires approval by the EC's College of Commissioners, will save RBS from hiving off the near-300 Williams & Glyn branches, having struggled to find a buyer ahead of its deadline which was set for the end of 2017.


The Royal Bank of Scotland Group plc - Special Call
Jul 12 17
To discuss the settlement reached with the Federal Housing Finance Agency regarding US RMBS claims


The Royal Bank of Scotland Group plc Reaches Settlement with Federal Housing Finance Agency
Jul 12 17
The Royal Bank of Scotland Group plc (together with its subsidiaries, "RBS") has reached a settlement with the Federal Housing Finance Agency ("FHFA") as conservator of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, to resolve claims by FHFA in relation to RBS's issuance and underwriting of approximately $32 billion (£25 billion) of residential mortgage-backed securities in the US. As part of the settlement, FHFA's outstanding litigation against RBS will be withdrawn. Under the settlement, RBS will pay FHFA $5.5 billion (£4.2 billion), of which $754 million (£581 million) will be reimbursed to RBS under indemnification agreements with third parties. The cost to RBS (net of the indemnity mentioned above) of $4.75 billion (£3.65 billion) is largely covered by existing provisions.


